'''Theophilos Kourkouas''' ({{lang-el|Θεόφιλος Κουρκούας}}, [[floruit|fl.]] ca. 920–960s) was a distinguished [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] general in the 10th century. He was also the grandfather of the [[Byzantine emperor]] [[John I Tzimiskes]] (r. 969–976).

==Biography==
Theophilos was a scion of the [[Kourkouas]] family, a clan of [[Armenians|Armenian]] origin that had established itself as one of the chief families among the [[Anatolia]]n military aristocracy by the early 10th century.{{sfn|Kazhdan|1991|pp=1156–1157}}{{sfn|Whittow|1996|pp=337–338}} His father was likely called Romanos, and he was possibly the grandson of [[John Kourkouas the Elder]], who served as commander of the [[Hikanatoi]] regiment and conspired against Emperors [[Basil I]] (r. 867–886) in the 870s.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Theophilos Kurkuas (#28152)}}{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|pp=58–59}} Theophilos is probably to be identified with the person referred to in contemporary Arabic and Armenian sources as ''ash-Shamīshāq'' or ''Ch‘mšshik'' respectively, indicating that he  already bore the surname or sobriquet of Tzimiskes, which was famously borne by his grandson, the Emperor [[John I Tzimiskes]] (r. 969–976).{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Theophilos Kurkuas (#28152)}}{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|p=66}} Although the Byzantine sources insist that this surname was given exclusively to the later emperor, and that it derived from the Armenian word for a type of small reddish sandals worn by women in the East,{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|pp=71–72}} it may well have derived from the river and homonymous town of Chimichgezek in the southern portion of the [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]] of [[Mesopotamia (theme)|Mesopotamia]], where presumably Theophilos was active, perhaps as the local ''[[strategos]]'' (military governor).{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|p=66}}

Theophilos was the younger brother of the celebrated general [[John Kourkouas]], who was appointed as [[Domestic of the Schools]] (i.e. supreme commander of the imperial armies) in circa 923 by Emperor [[Romanos Lekapenos]] (r. 920–944) and served in this post for 22 years.{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|pp=60–66}} Theophilos is first mentioned in 923,when along with his brother he suppressed of the revolt of the ''strategos'' of [[Chaldia]], [[Bardas Boilas]]. He succeeded the defeated rebel as governor of this strategically important province until ca. 940.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Theophilos Kurkuas (#28152)}}{{sfn|Runciman|1988|pp=70–71}} From 927 on, when John Kourkouas launched continuous campaigns against the neighbouring Muslim [[Thughur|border emirates]], Theophilos assisted him ably, especially in the direction of [[Medieval Armenia|Armenia]], and emerged as his brother's chief aide and lieutenant.{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|p=66}}{{sfn|Runciman|1988|pp=135ff.}} The history of [[Theophanes Continuatus]] laud his excellence and valour, and compared for his exploits in [[Upper Mesopotamia]] with [[Justinian I]]'s general [[Solomon (Byzantine general)|Solomon]].{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Theophilos Kurkuas (#28152)}}

According to the ''[[De administrando imperio]]'', from Chaldia Theophilos launched raids into the region of [[Basean]] (Phasiane in Greek), i.e. the eastern portions of the emirate of Qaliqala or [[Theodosiopolis (Armenia)|Theodosiopolis]] (modern [[Erzurum]]). At an unknown point he also secured the submission of the emirate of [[Avnik]], whose ruler was obliged to send his son as a hostage to [[Constantinople]].{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Theophilos Kurkuas (#28152)}}

Theodosiopolis finally fell in September 949, after seven months of siege.{{sfn|Runciman|1988|pp=139–140}}{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Theophilos Kurkuas (#28152)}} Theophilos was named ''strategos'' of the new theme of Theodosiopolis, and held the office at least until 952.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Theophilos Kurkuas (#28152)}} His fate thereafter is not known in detail, except for a brief mention in [[Theophanes Continuatus]] that he held the rank of ''[[magistros]]'' and the post of Domestic of the Schools under [[Nikephoros II Phokas]] (r. 963–969), possibly as an honorary appointment; according to Lisa Andriollo however this is a misinterpretation of the text, which actually refers to John Tzimiskes.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Theophilos Kurkuas (#28152)}}{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|p=67 (esp. note 48)}}

Theophilos's unnamed son married the sister of Nikephoros Phokas.{{sfn|Kazhdan|1991|pp=1156–1157}}{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|p=71}} The couple probably had several children,{{sfn|Andriollo|2012|p=71}} but their only known son is John Tzimiskes, who overthrew and murdered his uncle in 969, ruling as senior emperor until his death in 976.{{sfn|Kazhdan|1991|pp=1045, 1157}}

